I hear the same noise.

00:17:10.762 --> 00:17:12.564
It's like, really?!

00:17:12.564 --> 00:17:14.265 align:start size:84% position:16%
But it was not
coming from the bush.

00:17:14.265 --> 00:17:17.135
It was coming from that cliff.

00:17:17.135 --> 00:17:19.203
And at the bottom of the cliff,

00:17:19.203 --> 00:17:22.273
I just get on the edge of it,

00:17:22.273 --> 00:17:25.077
and I saw this little
crocodiles lined up,

00:17:25.077 --> 00:17:26.345
talking to mom.

00:17:27.846 --> 00:17:32.117 align:start size:94% position:6%
I discovered that day,
the call of the crocodile.

00:17:32.117 --> 00:17:34.186
Yes, scientific discovery.

00:17:34.186 --> 00:17:35.020
See?

00:17:36.187 --> 00:17:38.322
So I've been studying
this for a long time

00:17:38.322 --> 00:17:40.159
before I head off an expedition.

00:17:40.159 --> 00:17:44.662 align:start size:94% position:6%
Nobody could actually
tell me what was the trick

00:17:44.662 --> 00:17:47.699 align:start size:97% position:3%
to know if there was a
crocodile in the water or not.

00:17:47.699 --> 00:17:50.302
The Aboriginal people
used to go in the water

00:17:50.302 --> 00:17:53.771 align:start size:88% position:13%
with two stones, getting
inside the water,

00:17:53.771 --> 00:17:56.408
and smash the stones together.

00:17:56.408 --> 00:17:58.510 align:start size:81% position:19%
And then they make
a little noise,

00:17:58.510 --> 00:18:01.046
and then they will know if
there's a crocodile there.

00:18:01.046 --> 00:18:02.414
Well, that's a bit
too late, right,

00:18:02.414 --> 00:18:04.582 align:start size:81% position:19%
you're just in
the water already.

00:18:04.582 --> 00:18:07.386
It's like the supper thing.

